item.label: Cerebral sulci & fissures
item.name: Cerebral sulci_fissures
item.description: A cerebral fissure is AKA a cerebral sulcus (sing.); sulci (pl.).  Fissures are the depressions or grooves between the gyri or convolutions of the cerebral cortex.  Fissure generally refers to a sulcus that is particularly deep.  The terms are used interchangeably in some cases.

item.label: Central sulcus
item.name: Central sulcus
item.description: The central sulcus (of Rolando) is an important sulcus on the lateral aspect of the cerebral hemisphere that separates the frontal from the parietal lobes. It extends from just medial to the superior border of the hemisphere downward to the lateral or Sylvian fissure. The primary motor and somatosensory areas of cortex form the gyri (pre-central and post-central, respectively) on either side of this sulcus.

item.label: Parieto-occipital sulcus
item.name: Parieto-occipital sulcus
item.description: The parieto-occipital sulcus is a deep fissure that divides the parietal from the occipital lobes on the medial aspect of the cerebral hemisphere.

item.label: Calcarine fissure
item.name: Calcarine fissure
item.description: The calcarine fissure or sulcus is AKA as Area 17 of Brodmann. It is a prominent sulcus on the medial surface of the occipital lobe consisting of an upper bank (cuneus) and lower bank (lingual gyrus) where the neurons of the primary visual cortex are located.

item.label: Commissures
item.name: Commissures
item.description: The term 'commissure' refers to bundles of axons that cross the midline of the neuraxis and connect corresponding areas of the brain. Significant commissures in the brain are the corpus callosum, anterior and posterior commissures.  In the spinal cord, the anterior or ventral white commissure is very important.

item.label: Corpus callosum
item.name: Corpus callosum
item.description: The corpus callosum is a massive curved commissure that interconnects corresponding areas of the two cerebral hemispheres so that these areas may function in a coordinated manner.

item.label: Rostrum
item.name: Rostrum
item.description: The rostrum of the corpus callosum is a thin band of nerve fibers beneath the genu containing commissural fibers interconnecting the orbital cortices.

item.label: Genu
item.name: Genu
item.description: The genu is the sharp bend in the corpus callosum at it most anterior or rostral aspect.  The commissural fibers within the genu interconnect the frontal lobes.

item.label: Body
item.name: Body
item.description: The body of the lateral ventricle is located between the anterior horn, rostrally, and the atrium or trigone, caudally.

item.label: Splenium
item.name: Splenium
item.description: The splenium is the thick and rounded posterior aspect of the corpus callosum.  These commissural axons interconnect the occipital and temporal regions of the cerebral hemispheres.

item.label: Anterior commissure
item.name: Anterior commissure
item.description: The anterior commissure is a small and compact bundle of commissural axons located just beneath and caudal to the rostrum of the corpus callosum. It connects corresponding areas in the temporal cortices as well as olfactory structures.

item.label: Fornix, crus
item.name: Fornix, crus
item.description: The crus is that portion of the fornix between the fimbria and body of the fornix. It curves superiorly to just beneath the splenium of the corpus callosum.

item.label: Internal capsule, Genu
item.name: Internal capsule, genu
item.description: The genu of the internal capsule is located where the anterior and posterior limbs meet. It includes connections between the ventral anterior (VA) and ventral lateral (VL) thalamic nuclei with the motor/premotor cerebral cortex as well as corticopontine fibers.

item.label: Corpus striatum,Caudate nucl,Head
item.name: Corpus striatum Cauda
item.description: The caudate nucleus is the medial portion of the striatum. It consists of a large head that bulges into the anterior horn of the lateral ventricle, a body that narrows and curves along the body of the lateral ventricle and a tail that continues through the atrium or trigone of the lateral ventricle and into the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle. Principal connections are with the prefrontal and other association areas of cerebral cortex.

item.label: Diencephalon
item.name: Diencephalon
item.description: Developmentally, the diencephalon and telencephalon are derived from the most anterior aspect of the developing neural tube, i.e. the prosencephalon. It includes the thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus and subthalamus. The retina, optic nerve and tract and neurohypophysis are also considered to be part of the diencephalon since they are formed as outgrowths from the diencephalon.

item.label: Thalamus
item.name: Thalamus
item.description: The thalamus is a large collection of nuclei that have major connections with the cerebral cortex involving both sensory and motor functions. Some thalamic nuclei have very specific connections relative to visual, auditory and somatosensory afferents and their projection to specific areas of cerebral cortex, while other nuclei have more general inputs and connections with association areas of cerebral cortex.

item.label: Centomedian nucleus
item.name: Centomedian nucleus
item.description: The centromedian nucleus is the largest of the intralaminar nuclei of the thalamus.  It receives afferent input from the globus pallidus and sends efferents to the striatum and diffuse projections to widespread areas of cerebral cortex.

item.label: Lateral dorsal nucleus
item.name: Lateral dorsal nucleus
item.description: The lateral dorsal nucleus of the thalamus sends efferents to the posterior aspect of the cingulate gyrus.

item.label: Medial dorsal nucleus
item.name: Medial dorsal nucleus
item.description: The dorsomedial nucleus of the thalamus (DM) is AKA the medial dorsal nucleus.  It is located medial to the internal medullary lamina of the thalamus.  It has important connections with the prefrontal association cortex and the limbic system.

item.label: Pulvinar
item.name: Pulvinar
item.description: The pulvinar is the largest of the thalamic nuclei. It has connections with parietal-occipital-temporal association cerebral cortex.

item.label: Ventral anterior nucleus
item.name: Ventral anterior nucleus
item.description: The ventral anterior thalamic nucleus (VA) is the thalamic relay for motor control. It receives input form the basal ganglia, cerebellum and cerebral cortex and projects to the motor and premotor cortex via the internal capsule.

item.label: Ventral lateral nucleus
item.name: Ventral lateral nucleus
item.description: The ventral lateral thalamic nucleus (VL) is the thalamic relay for motor control. It receives input form the basal ganglia, cerebellum and cerebral cortex and projects to the motor and premotor cortex via the internal capsule.

item.label: Ventral posterior medial nucleus
item.name: Vent. post. medial nucleu
item.description: The ventral posteromedial thalamic nucleus (VPM) deals with somatosensory information from the head. Input to this nucleus is from the trigeminothalamic tracts. It sends efferents to post-central gyrus of cerebral cortex via the posterior limb of the internal capsule.

item.label: Subthalamic nucleus
item.name: Subthalamic nucleus
item.description: The subthalamic nucleus is a bi-convex lens-shaped nucleus located just medial and superior to the junction of the internal capsule and crus cerebri. The subthalamic nucleus is part of an indirect route through the basal ganglia whereby it receives input from the external segment of the globus pallidus and returns it output to the internal segment of the globus pallidus. Damage to the subthalamic nucleus produces hemiballismus on the contralateral side of the body.

item.label: Visual pathway
item.name: Visual pathway
item.description: The entire visual pathway begins in the retina and terminates in the calcarine cortex of the occipital lobe.  The components of the pathway are the optic nerve, optic chiasm, optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus and optic radiations.

item.label: Optic tract
item.name: Optic tract
item.description: The Optic tract consists of optic nerve axons that serve the contralateral visual field.  These axons originate in the ipsilateral temporal retina and contralateral nasal retina and terminate in the lateral geniculate nucleus as well as the pretectal area.

item.label: Line of Gennari
item.name: Line of Gennari
item.description: The Line of Gennari is AKA the Stripe of Gennari.  It is a thin, white stripe in the primary visual cortex of the calcarine cortex. Visual cortex is often called striate cortex because of this line that is visible to the naked eye.

item.label: Midbrain
item.name: Midbrain
item.description: The midbrain is AKA the mesencephalon. Within its parts (tectum, tegmentum, substantia nigra and cerebral crus or basis pedunculi), it contains cranial nerve nuclei, all of the clinically important ascending and descending tracts, etc. It is traversed by the cerebral aqueduct or aqueduct of Sylvius. It originates developmentally from the mesencephalon.

item.label: Somatosensory tracts
item.name: Somatosensory tracts
item.description: The somatosensory tracts include the dorsal column-medial lemniscal, spinothalamic and trigeminothalamic.  They terminate in the ventral posterior nucleus of the thalamus after traveling through the brain stem.

item.label: Substantia nigra
item.name: Substantia nigra
item.description: The substantia nigra is a large band-like nucleus in the midbrain located between the crus cerebri and the red nuclei of the tegmentum. It has two parts: 1) a compact portion consisting of closely packed dopaminergic neurons filled with neuromelanin pigment. These neurons project to the striatum & are the ones damaged in Parkinson disease; 2) a reticular portion consisting of loosely packed neurons that receive input from the striatum and project to the thalamus.

item.label: Cerebral crus
item.name: Cerebral crus
item.description: The cerebral crus is AKA the crus cerebri or the basis pedunculi. This most ventral or inferior aspect of the paired cerebral peduncles contains motor axons originating primarily in the cerebral cortex. The bulk of the cerebral crus is made up of the corticospinal, corticobulbar and corticopontine tract fibers that have left the cerebral cortex, traveled through the internal capsule and will terminate in the spinal cord and brain stem.

item.label: Oculomotor nerve
item.name: Oculomotor nerve
item.description: The third or oculomotor cranial nerve provides motor innervation to the ipsilateral medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, inferior oblique and levator palapebrae muscles that move the eye. It also includes parasympathetic fibers that terminate in the ipsilateral ciliary ganglion; post-ganglionic fibers from the ciliary ganglion innervate the constrictors of the pupil and the ciliary muscles.

item.label: Pons
item.name: Pons
item.description: The pons is that portion of the brainstem between the midbrain and medulla. It consists of a basilar or basal portion that contains structures primarily associated with motor control and a tegmental portion that contains cranial nerve nuclei and important sensory tracts. The cerebellum overlies the pons and medulla. The rostral aspect of the fourth ventricle is located on the dorsal surface of the pons. The pons and cerebellum originate embryologically from the metencephalon of the hindbrain.

item.label: Cerebellum
item.name: Cerebellum
item.description: The cerebellum is sometimes referred to as the 'small' brain.  It is located within the posterior fossa, superior to the brain stem. It consists of a finely convoluted cortical surface of folia, a central core of white matter (AKA medullary center) and four paired deep nuclei (dentate, emboliform, fastigial and globose) embedded within the white matter core. The cerebellum functions in the planning and coordination of movement.

item.label: Cortex
item.name: Cortex
item.description: The outer cortical surface of the cerebellum is folded into fine-caliber ridges called folia.  This cortex consists of three layers, an outer molecular layer, an inner granular layer and a Purkinje cell layer in the middle at the junction of the molecular and granular layers.

item.label: Medullary center
item.name: Medullary center
item.description: The medullary center of the cerebellum is the white matter in the center of the cerebellum.  It is composed of the nerve fibers traveling to and from the cerebellar cortex and deep cerebellar nuclei.

item.label: Emboliform nucleus
item.name: Emboliform nucleus
item.description: The emboliform nucleus is one of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum located medial to the dentate nucleus and lateral to the globose nucleus. In non-human species it is combined with the globose nucleus as a single nuclear mass and called the 'interposed' nucleus or 'nucleus interpositus'; this term is commonly used in human neuroanatomy as well. It receives input from the paravermal zone of cerebellar cortex and projects its output via the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus and the red nucleus.

item.label: Middle cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Middle cerebellar peduncl
item.description: The middle cerebellar peduncle consists exclusively of pontocerebellar tract fibers that take their origin from pontine nuclei in the contralateral basilar pons. Thus, it carries afferent information to cerebellum from the contralateral cerebral cortex via the corticopontine to pontine nuclei to pontocerebellar tract.

item.label: Inferior cerebellar penducle
item.name: Inferior cerebellar pendu
item.description: The inferior cerebellar peduncle is AKA the restiform body. Located on the lateral aspect of the medulla, it includes multiple tracts afferent to the cerebellum including the uncrossed dorsal or posterior spinocerebellar, cuneocerebellar, vestibulocerebellar, reticulocerebellar and crossed olivocerebellar. It also includes some cerebellar output tracts such as those projecting to the reticular formation and the vestibular nuclei.

item.label: Ventricular system, Lateral ventricle
item.name: Ventricular system La
item.description: The lateral ventricle is a large, C-shaped space within each cerebral hemisphere that is filled with cerebrospinal fluid. It consists of an anterior (or frontal) horn that extends into the frontal lobe, a body, a posterior (or occipital) horn that extends into the occipital lobe, an inferior (or temporal) horn that extends into the temporal lobe and the atrium or trigone where the body, posterior limb and inferior limb meet.

item.label: Anterior horn
item.name: Anterior horn
item.description: The anterior horn of the lateral ventricle is AKA the frontal horn. This region of the lateral ventricle extends into the frontal lobe.

item.label: Body
item.name: Body_1
item.description: The body of the lateral ventricle is located between the anterior horn, rostrally, and the atrium or trigone, caudally.
